<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1507,2037]" pageId="4" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis box="[199,362,1759,1785]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="15">Redescription.</emphasis>
FW costa length: 
<quantity box="[563,642,1759,1786]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="15.0">15 mm</quantity>
(
<typeStatus box="[655,764,1759,1786]" pageId="4" pageNumber="15">lectotype</typeStatus>
), costa and outer margin highly bent resulting rounded apex; female dorsal wing surface brown; ventral wing surface medial pattern composed of a continous white line, a lighter brown bordered basally, but dark brown distally running from middle costa to tornus; ventral wing surface inner margin medial area with red scaling. Male is not known.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1507,2037]" pageId="4" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis box="[199,320,1904,1929]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="15">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The species can be easily recognized on the basis of the unique HW ventral surface pattern; the most remarkable trait is the continuous median line, which is bent and not zigzagged or dashed. On the basis of the observation that the sexual dimorphism in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar &amp; Constantino" authorityYear="1995" box="[569,692,1975,2001]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Johnsonita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[569,692,1975,2001]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="15">Johnsonita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
expressed by the dorsal wingsurfaces is moderate, we hypothetise that the hitherto unkown male phenotype has also brown dorsal wings surfaces.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,501]" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis box="[199,344,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Distribution.</emphasis>
Geographical: 
<collectingCountry box="[521,669,151,177]" name="Colombia" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">COLOMBIA</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[686,770,151,177]" country="Colombia" name="Bogota" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Bogotá</collectingRegion>
) (
<figureCitation box="[796,883,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="39.[151,250,1742,1766]" captionTargetBox="[251,1396,204,1718]" captionTargetId="figure-18@39.[192,1396,181,1718]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURE 30. Johnsonita distributions based on museum material examinded. J. assula = red circle, J. carpia = yellow trinagle, J. catadupa = blue diamond, J. chalamydem = brown triangle, J. ianusca = green square, J. oxalida = purple diamond." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4711325" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4711325/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
); spatial: recorded between elevations 3000 and 
<quantity box="[151,236,187,213]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" unit="m" value="3200.0">3200 m</quantity>
a.s.l; temporal: recorded in April.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,501]" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis box="[199,260,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Note.</emphasis>
The species was placed in the monotypic Assula-Gruppe by Draudt (l.c.) between his “Satyrioides-Gruppe” (= genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Kaye, 1904" authorityName="Kaye" authorityYear="1904" box="[307,547,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Macusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[307,403,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Macusia</emphasis>
Kaye, 1904
</taxonomicName>
, and “Marsyas-Gruppe” (= genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Wallengren, 1858" authorityName="Wallengren" authorityYear="1858" box="[939,1322,258,285]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Pseudolycaena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[939,1109,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Pseudolycaena</emphasis>
Wallengren, 1858
</taxonomicName>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Robbins" editor="Lamas, G." firstAuthor="Robbins" journalOrPublisher="Scientific Publishers, Gainesville, Florida" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" pagination="118 - 137" refId="ref23342" refString="Robbins, R. K. (2004 b) Lycaenidae. Theclinae. Tribe Eumaeini,. In: Lamas, G. (Ed.), Checklist: Part 4 A. Hesperioidea - Papilionoidea. In: Heppner, J. B. (Ed.), Atlas of Neotropical Lepidoptera. Vol. 5 A. Association for Tropical Lepidoptera, Scientific Publishers, Gainesville, Florida, pp. 118 - 137." title="Lycaenidae. Theclinae. Tribe Eumaeini" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Checklist: Part 4 A. Hesperioidea - Papilionoidea. In: Heppner, J. B" year="2004" yearSuffix="b">Robbins (2004b)</bibRefCitation>
transferred this species from 
<taxonomicName authority="Fabricius, 1807" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1807" box="[589,857,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Thecla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[589,665,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Thecla</emphasis>
Fabricius, 1807
</taxonomicName>
, to the genus 
<emphasis box="[1024,1154,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar &amp; Constantino" authorityYear="1995" box="[1024,1151,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Johnsonita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Johnsonita</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Robbins (op. cit.) put a question- mark beside the name. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Draudt" authorityYear="1919" box="[531,632,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Thecla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="assula">
<emphasis box="[531,632,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">J. assula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the typical 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar &amp; Constantino" authorityYear="1995" box="[815,938,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Johnsonita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[815,938,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Johnsonita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
wing shape, but the ventral wing pattern is somewhat unusual with the medial line running to the tornus. The male is unknown. For a long time the species was known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[395,443,403,429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">type</typeStatus>
material. Another female specimen was taken in 2008 at approximately 
<quantity box="[1257,1346,403,429]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" unit="m" value="3000.0">3000 m</quantity>
. a.s.l. at one of the hills overlooking Bogotá (probably: Cerro 
<collectingCountry box="[756,889,439,465]" name="Montserrat" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Monserrate</collectingCountry>
); more recently J. F. Le Crom (
<collectingCountry box="[1242,1356,439,466]" name="Colombia" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Colombia</collectingCountry>
) found another female at around the same altitude on a hilltop at El Tablazo (Warren-Gash, pers. comm.).
</paragraph>
